<user_name>Ken Monk</user_name><Time>1530733254232<//Time>< rate>
2</rate>
< Text>
Wow how times have changed. I've fished the Toronado for 30 years since I was a kid. Went a week and a half ago on an "Angeler's Chronicles" trip, posted on their Facebook page and by Ray himself as a discounted trip on 976-Tuna, but there was no discount. In fact there was a mandatory jackpot and an additional  $10 squid fee. I have never in my life paid more for bait getting on any boat from San Diego to Morro Bay.
We were the last boat at San Clemente. The Ultra and the Thunderbird there long before and anchored. We left the island early, but they cruised back at 8 knots the slowest I've seen. Saving diesel were we?
Hey Ray, if you are hurting for money just change your prices. Don't advertise a discount you don't give. Pretty sad, I caught my first yellowtail and first albacore on that boat and with Ray, but likely I'll spend my money elsewhere going forward.
No one from Pierpoint Landing, Angeler's Chronicles or the Toronado even had the decency to answer me back about the advertised discount. Let alone the additional charges for mandatory jackpot and squid.
Buyer beware. Photos are from Angeler's Chronicles Facebook and the last 976-Tuna post Ray did where he offers the discount on the audio message.</Text>

< Rating>

< review>
I took my boys (ages 5 & 7) and my wife fishing on the So Cal. Wasn't expecting much heard mixed reviews but instead a got a lot of great help and words of encouragement from the crew.The Crew was skipper Mitch deckhands were Phil and Justin. They went above and beyond to help my family enjoy themselves fishing. They took fish off the hook which were sculpins and they are poisonous. I have been fishing for about 28 years on these boats and know how some deck hands can be. What a relief it was on the first of many tangles that the deckhand had to cut our line but retied it immediately. I did not have to stop what i was doing to fix my kids pole. Never once heard a foul word about anything from the crew. I was a profession crew ( I think this is there A crew) they should be recognized for a great job. I would highly recommend this boat with this crew to anyone. Just remember patients they are trying to get to everyone on the boat(when the counts are better they do better so they want you to catch as many fish as you can. I am happy that my kids had so much fun and look forward to fishing on the So Cal again soon. one last thing the skipper even let my boy up on the bridge to see all the stuff up their. A Crew thanks for such a wonderful time on your boat.<//review>

<UserId.>107845669361881580654</UserId.><username>Martin Cremer< /username>< Date>
1537157293983< /Date>
< rating>
5< /rating>
<Text>I am new to off shore fishing in southern California. I think it's safe to say that there is nothing quite like this sport-fishing culture. Those that go on the overnight and multi-day trips are mostly intense and focused fisherman. Even for those with ample deep sea experience there's no way to prepare for these trips. You have to dive in and just try to keep up. Never in my life have I met harder working people than the crew of the Toronado. Everyone from the captain (Sean #1) to the deck hands Sandab (Patrick) and Sean #2 are passionate and kind people. I approached them with endless questions and they were so helpful. They all took the time to impart their knowledge of fishing southern California. The captain loaned me his own rod when I found myself ill equipt to deal with the bluefin we were targeting. Sandab tied my knots and slowly demonstrated his technique empathizing the importance of practicing with your own gear (he too let me try his favored rod). Sean on the deck helped me time and again with finding good bait, he showed me how to hook them for different scenarios, and he quietly came over to untangle my birds nests before I caused any major tangles.

These guys live this work. They are out on the water day after day working backbreaking hours. If you are respectful, if you pay attention to their advice, and find the right moment to approach for help, you will learn a lot from both the crew and fellow anglers. We had a rough day to say the least. Some people were understandably frustrated as the swells pounded the ship and the boiling patches of tuna wouldn't even try to bite the baits. The boat was 100% full. The captain fished hard to the last minute. Despite the less than stellar day, I realized I was hooked on this socal fishing. I'm writing this review as I wait to board a ship heading out for a 3 night trip on what will be my third offshore this week! This is your go to place in the LA area for sportfishing. Thank you to the whole crew of the Toronado for your warm hospitality and your hard work. I will never forget my time on the Toronado and I look forward to seeing you all again!<//Text>< Pics>
None< /Pics>

<user_name>Sergio I. Cortes Jr< /user_name>< review>
I contacted West Coast Auto Glass late on a Saturday for a windshield replacement on a 2010 Honda Accord Crosstour. Manny took the call and personally assisted me with booking the appointment for Monday morning. I made mention of a 149.95 windshield replacement coupon I had found in a free advertising publication and he said he would honor it.

I wish to state my extreme satisfaction with their service. When I contacted Manny on Monday morning to confirm the appointment he informed me the windshield for the Crosstour was substantially higher than the one for the Accord, which he had initially found in his reference materials to quote the service. He told me he would still honor the coupon price and proceeded to confirm the appointment. He saved me over 100.00 dollars in comparison with all the other outfits I had contacted to get quotes. This was of great value to me since lease on the Crosstour was expiring in under a month, I did not have to spend a lot of money on a repair for a vehicle I would not own any longer.

His techinician was polite and properly attired and he showed up right on time. He was courteous and his demeanor was excellent. He finished the job in under an hour.

I would definitely recommend West Coast Auto Glass to anyone. I will make sure I hold on to that coupon in case I ever need his services again.</review>

<gmap_id>0x80c336788a535be3:0xb34d8893385eb460< /gmap_id><Rating>5<//Rating><UserId.>102595754669143238620<//UserId.><Name>Rafa Bastida<//Name><Pictures>None<//Pictures><response>{'time': 1605873979950, 'text': 'Thank you'}</response></record></dataset><record>

<user_name>Jeanette O.</user_name><UserId.>114396842253496589744<//UserId.><rate>5<//rate>< Date>
1578381618220</Date>
<GmapID>0x80c336788a535be3:0xb34d8893385eb460< /GmapID>< Review>
The closest, and really only, legitimate and good quality baklava I ever knew about used to be a 40 min drive (that's without California traffic). Now? It's a sliver of that. Sea of Sweet is the classic mom and pop bakery that caters to the traditional Arabic desserts that I can be so proud of BECAUSE it's local and the owner, George, MAKES you want to come back-- which I did. Both times that I've been there, it just feels as though I'm in an extention of George's home. He has a great warmth to him.
The Turkish coffee is great #TheRightKindOfCoffee, AND he brings it right to you. The desserts are delicious; the baklava is sweet, but it's not overwhelming. Haven't tried the shakes/ smoothies yet, but can't wait to give them a taste.
Overall, a solid thumbs up.<//Review>

<date>1499042227902<//date><Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
Great spot for a quick treat. Fresh crepes, smoothies and handmade pastries all of which are absolutely delicious. The owner is incredibly friendly, you can tell he enjoys being there and making a customer feel at home. I tried the armo savory crepe which was salty and tasty with heavily spiced cured beef (not spicy, spiced) and ashta cream (kinda like a unsalted cottage cheese/cream cheese). Not bad, definitely different. Also tried the Lebanese delight, fresh strawberries ashta cream and honey. That was really good. If you're in the area definitely give this place a try.< /review>

< date>
1532327100906< /date>
< user>
107915918624618371469< /user>
< review>
Ladies and Gentlemen.

I am Lebanese, Beiruty to be exact.
I am an avid Lebanese sweets connoisseur from the home land to the U.S. East Coast to the West Coast.

One day a friend I follow put up a picture of the Rio from Sea Of Sweet. Immediately it reminded me of the cocktails that are very popular in Lebanon. So curiosity kicks in and I look up the page. Surprise, another Lebanese sweet shop. So I bookmark and monitor.
A few months pass and I am strongly craving a Knafe triggered by a friends post of FB while he was in Beirut. So I look at the list of places that I know that make it and prepare myself to be disappointed as usual. But then I remembered the drink. I said to myself. If this place can make a drink like this and the pictures of the sweets really look tempting so it may be worth the 1.5 hour drive to get this and if they fall through, well at least I tried it. So off I go, sitting through that horrible L.A. traffic as usual.

At arrival I notice it was in a small shopping plaza, kind of inconspicuous. Walk in and the shop is brightly lit and the sweets are on display. I see the Knafe, but I hesitate. I think to myself. How long has this been out sitting there? So I digress and look at the petit four and ask to taste. The Owner was kind and was 100% looking to please. Real Lebanese hospitality. I like the Chocolate covered petit four and Halwaiet il Jibin. So I take a Kilo of both. I wanted a drink and thought to myself that the Rio will be it. But as I walked over to the side I saw the Knafe again. I couldn't hold myself back this time. I asked him if it was fresh. He answered me Honestly with a no, but he did have one currently on if I was willing to wait. I smiled from his gratitude and hospitality. I agreed and had a seat in the far side of the store.

While I wait, In the other corner I see his son and daughter talking. It was fun to sit in this place and watch a family run it. Customers walking in and quickly being greeted by name, these must be the usuals. Return customers means you are doing it right. People tell me that new are key to a good business, but I have to disagree. Though new are important to increase revenue, the return customer will keep you open.
A couple walked in. Obvious they were new, just like I was. They looked at the sweets unsure of what to try or do. They didn't look like they knew middle eastern sweets other than the usual baklawah. I knew they were there for the Rio drink and a crepe though since that is what they kept talking about when kept looking at their phone. Owner quickly acknowledged them and told them to taste what they wanted. They both smiled and had a taste of the petit four and ordered the drink and crepe they wanted. Smiling and happily talking and excited. Taking pictures of the goodies. Eventually their drink and crepe arrived and the pictures continued. The looked amazed at the fruit piled high and the first taste was met with a shake of the head with enjoyment like Mark Wiens ;)

I see my Knafe arrive. I ordered it on a plate. So I can have it plain and simple. To really know and taste if it is what i'm looking for without it being covered by syrup soaked bread/Ka'ak.

Using only a fork the cheese is melt away stringy. Perfect. The fine Semolina crust is cooked to a golden crispy crust. Perfect. I dab the syrup and it was simple and a hint of fragrance. Perfect.
I raise my fork with melty cheese attached, I am no longer able to focus on anything else. This is it. This is the Knafe that i'm looking for. This is the taste that I miss that used to be at the old Victory Bakery. Just excellent. Not too Soft, just Smooth. Not salty hard cheese. Good texture of chewy mixed with the sweet syrup. The crust just crispy and crumbly enough.
Amazing! We now have a Great Knafe place on the West Coast again. Thank You!

Enjoy and Stay Wild!< /review>
<gmap_id>0x80c336788a535be3:0xb34d8893385eb460< /gmap_id>< Rate>
5</Rate>
<username>Mo Mo</username></record>

< review>
My husband felt like eating knafe and I saw this place and got a couple to try it out. We are  kind of picky as we have eaten knafe in Dearborn and Chicago. Who would have thought that we would find something so good in Rancho! They don't skimp like other places in California do and they people working there are very approachable and friendly. < username>
Adnan Hussain</username>

< date>
1598720208708< /date>
<GmapID>0x80c2a37ba2a581fb:0x442c2938801a9316< /GmapID>< user>
109937767140071494287</user>
<rate>5</rate><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOKqEF1kH1Wlhiyn1DuWaALehIdviocWkAscbFS=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPpK-r27C2AJIoTkj5vJJUlel227tWgRgTaPJR5=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pics><resp>None<//resp>< review>
Love walking along here or just chilling on the grass sometimes. One of the best locations to view the ocean, mountains and hear life moving around during sunrise and sunset. Also, tons of beautiful people to see while smelling the Pacific ocean and getting a leisurely walk in.

I know there are bathrooms, but haven't used them since I'm a local, but it's good to know they are there. If you continue along the path you'll come to the Santa Monica Pier and make a nice walk out of it, or turn up Montana Ave and visit the trendy and local shops that don't have as much tourist traffic as the Promenade. I love walking along the path when it's foggy, it gives the blouelvard a magical feeling.

Yes, there are homeless people, but this is LA and we are in an Apocalypse - I mean, Pandemic - so you know, there's that.</review>

< rate>
5</rate>
< Review>
Great place to unwind and go for a walk, have a picnic, or enjoy a cup of Joe while strolling through the park. In the warmer months, there are Personal Trainers training clients in the sun (maybe you could take a class with one of them & work on your tan while working out?). Such a beautiful space and very thankful for the City of Santa Monica & the State of CA maintaining these grounds. This is a great place to catch a Sunset as well; watching the Sunset against the foothills while over looking the water is astounding!<//Review>

< rate>
5</rate>
< Text>
Beautiful, peaceful, clean, safe. Gorgeous views of the ocean. The palms are unique to many others found in Southern California. They branch of from the root and create precious little places to sit in if you're having time to yourself. Plenty of food and gathering, entertainment, etc. but a much mellower feeling than, say, Venice Beach. This is not a spot convenient for those with little money, but there is a food truck and a few places nearby. A lovely place for a picnic and a walk.< /Text>

< Review>
Love this Santa Monica park overlooking the famous Pier and Pacific Ocean. It's clean, has public restrooms that are usually well kept, and offers some interesting people watching opportunities. Especially a relief on a hot day, with a steady cool ocean breeze. Free street parking on Montana and other side streets.< /Review>

< review>
Located in the heart of Santa Monica, nothing can beat its location,  views and fame! Lately there were improvements with the beach access - staircases are more frequent and accessible with bridges to cross the PCH. I found a little harder to park nearby. Other then that - you can stroll, bicycle, run, walk your dog, go all the way to the Santa Monica Pier, sit and enjoy the views,  take photos, eat, go over to the beach... the possibilities are endless!</review>

< Text>
Its always nice to walk in Santa Monica. I go there for many reasons. Sometimes just for some shopping  and sometimes just to walk down to the beach and watch the ocean while clearing my mind. I feel alot of us living here in Los Angeles are exposed to a lot of stress, but my calm moments are usually just to watch the sunset and hearing the sound of the waves,I guess going through some stress for me is worth it aslong I can go down to the ocean!!< /Text>

< text>
Located in the heart of Santa Monica, nothing can beat its location,  views and fame! Lately there were improvements with the beach access - staircases are more frequent and accessible with bridges to cross the PCH. I found a little harder to park nearby. Other then that - you can stroll, bicycle, run, walk your dog, go all the way to the Santa Monica Pier, sit and enjoy the views,  take photos, eat, go over to the beach... the possibilities are endless!< /text>

< Rating>
4</Rating>
< Review>
An aesthetically-pleasing strip of well-manicured grass, shrubs and palm trees, this park is located alongside a bluff overlooking the Pacific Ocean in Santa Monica. The city scrupulously maintains the park, and it is quite pretty.

Unfortunately, it‚Äôs often crowded by people who enjoy being watched while they work out their ridiculously well-toned, west-coast sculpted bodies. I sometimes wonder what would actually happen if an obese man were to sweat out a fifteen-minute CrossFit routine on his AirPods in the park. Surely he would be arrested within minutes. The police probably would be sympathetic to a degree. And surely he would be consoled by several young people sporting ‚Äúmom jean‚Äù athleisurewear.

They might as well just set up a BMI measuring device to screen anyone entering the park.<//Review>

<user>105797426705734058523</user><Name>Ashley Sundquist< /Name><time>1507904998826</time><rating>5< /rating><Text>Palisades Park is one of the most beautiful places in Santa Monica. There are panoramic views of the Pacific Ocean just beyond the massive bluff and you won't catch a better sunset in this part of town!

This is the ideal place to go for a walk, lay out a blanket and read, play with your dog, practice some yoga or have a picnic. There are park benches if you don't like to sit in the grass.

Pro tip:
- Pack a blanket or beach towel
- Bring some snacks
- Arrive about 20 minutes before sunset for world-class views</Text><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOClCr8zEDugGWgk7MJnGFrVaaIwHtHpg0LBTqB=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPzhuLNph_P4H0jPQd9KxqH726Bhm56vgGOZ-Ss=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOnNGi0zl5PLld20Xv97A5YemDoGVVPlIwhaVfe=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pictures>< resp>

<user_id>106059699316362119923< /user_id><name>Joey ‚ÄúSesame Numbnuts‚Äù Wisdom</name><date>1584575247695<//date><rating>5</rating>< review>
Unlike most traditional parks, this one extends along the bluffs like one long strip, going parallel with as well as overlooking the coast. One can get the surreal feeling as if this is the edge of the world, being on top of the cliffs, just above the ocean.  It may as well be considered that, since this is exactly where route 66 ends its great journey! To top off the Palisades Park, it's the ultimate place to go and bring a significant other, a child, a relative , yourself to go and work out, etc! Regardless if you're familiar with it or have been there a few hundred times, it truly never gets tiring..< /review>

It's really clean considering the amount of homeless people and tourist littering. Good luck finding parking next to the side walk it's close to impossible and if you do the meters are locked at 2hrs maximum. Best to just park in a parking building or structure and walk. This is by far one of the nicest spots to get a good view of the sun set definitely recommend.</text></record></dataset><record>

< Time>
1588811646283</Time>
<resp>None<//resp>< Text>
Always nice. The park is long and older so are the facilities. You can't beat the view! Many people exercise here. Outdoor yoga, doggy walking, running and chilling. There are steps to the beach at different points. (these include foot bridges across PCH) parking is tough and restrooms aren't great (though maintained) due to the homeless population. The park has made efforts to improve. Footpaths are maintained as is the lawn. BUT, it's all closed off with chain link fence (May 5 2020) due to the Pandemic. I'm sure it will open up again soon so the rest of my review stands.< /Text>

<user>111827535437084956662<//user>< name>
Loni Anderson</name>
<Date>1588811646283</Date><rate>4< /rate>< Review>
Always nice. The park is long and older so are the facilities. You can't beat the view! Many people exercise here. Outdoor yoga, doggy walking, running and chilling. There are steps to the beach at different points. (these include foot bridges across PCH) parking is tough and restrooms aren't great (though maintained) due to the homeless population. The park has made efforts to improve. Footpaths are maintained as is the lawn. BUT, it's all closed off with chain link fence (May 5 2020) due to the Pandemic. I'm sure it will open up again soon so the rest of my review stands.< /Review>

< review>
We came a little after 5 PM traffic was still a little packed but we found a great spot to park for 10 dollars. We walked for about 4 minutes to get to a nice spot and the greatest thing about it was that  It wasn't crowded at all, there were a few people here and they all seemed to be relaxing, enjoy the slight overcast. It was starting to get a little chilly for a while but then the clouds dissapeard and we got some amazing sun. It was so fresh and soothing, the waves were coming in pretty high which added wonderful, natural tension releasing sounds. This is just really a great area to sit and relax. You won't be dissapointed.<//review>

<review>Gorgeous views!< /review>< user>
109848170534779530358< /user>
<gmapID>0x80c2a37ba2a581fb:0x442c2938801a9316<//gmapID><rating>5</rating><time>1615507070777<//time></record></dataset><record>
<review>I love coming for walks here. Starting at san Vicente and going to the pier it is a beautiful flat area to take a stroll or a jog. You can see people enjoying picnics, taking pictures of the ocean in the background, or exercising. As you go through the park there are benches to sit on to take in the view. Artwork to appreciate and a beautiful rose garden.  If you haven't been I highly recommend checking it out.
Bonus: you can bring your dog along for the walk!< /review>< gmapID>

Palisades Park is a 5-acre park linear park overlooking the Pacific and its a wonderful place for walkers, bikers and people watchers, and exercise workout. Park is located between Colorado Avenue and Adelaide Drive above Highway 1. The PP is organized and well kept.  Street metered parking available. Overall, I highly recommend you visit this park in Santa Monica.< /text>

Santa Monica ,California! What is not to like! Look at the scenery. Look out at the Pacific Ocean. Magnificent. You can smell the salt in the air. < review>
How can you go wrong at a beach?!
Well.. rough turn off into the parking lot from either direction... a clean public restroom, which is nice to use while on the road, but also means PUBLIC restroom - it's on the beach. Beautiful boardwalk down the middle of the sand, not quite reaching the water, but still provides a pretty dayum  picturesque view of the SoCals.... I really enjoyed it. Keep in mind, I am ridiculously optimistic and the water gives me the jollies. ü§ô</review>

This park is a big reason why Santa Monica is such an awesome place to live!</Review>

<GmapID>0x80c2a37ba2a581fb:0x442c2938801a9316</GmapID>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>
<UserId.>110653898983121183393< /UserId.>< Name>
George Smith< /Name>
< text>
.  Palisades Park is a great place to watch a beautiful Californua sunset over Santa Monica Bay. It runs along  a top of a cliff overlooking the beach. For the bike path you gotta go down to the beach below because the park just has one wide paved walkway but its great for jogging and the park has plenty of nice places tor spreading out your lawn chair or yoga mat or to come to with your coffee and magazine from Barnes and Noble just two blocks away. There is a rose garden and a statue of Santa Monica, and the park is nicely landscaped with plenty of shade trees. There are public restrooms a few blocks north after you cross thevstreet where PCH comes up and down around Wilshire but their a long walk from where the park starts at the pier. Further north theres a big picknick area with tables and benches and I think I even saw some BBQ's built in to the masonry.
Besides the pier entrance there are I think four more access's to the beach from the park via several stairs, switch backs and trails which might be a little awkward if your carrying alot of stuff or your an old fart like me. I usualy make it down ok and take the air lift to the hospital from about half way back up.
There's parking along the street but your not going to get it unless you come early in the day. Not to worry though as the park is only two blocks away from the Third St Prominade with all its shops, restaurants, movie theaters and outdoor kiosks and entertainers, alot of whom are really high class and bring everything from their own pianos to a whole trumpet section, it's a blast. And there is of course alot of parking structures and the park and the prominade run parrelel to each other all the way from the pier entrance to Wilshire Blvd.
This is a must see for out of towners who plan on going back and bragging about where they've been to. Route 66 ends right at the pier entrance at the iconic pier sign thats appeared in a million movies like Forrest Gump. There's also a cannon left over from WWII's Battle of Santa Monica Bay that kids love to ride and has a barrel big enough to stick your head into. Great photo ops both and the pier is just down from the park entrance. It's a tough climb back up if your carrying kids and strollers but theres a great  carousel in a building that you maybrevognize, arcade and amusement park with a ferris wheel that overlooks the ocean. You can rent bikes right by the carosel and peddle up the bike path along the beach with a beautiful view of the bay and the Santa Monica mountains or go the other way and peddle down to Venice and Muscle Beach for more shops and outdoor entertainment, local vendors, card readers and a general atmosphere and scene right out of the 60's.
The pier and park entrance are just a short walk away from the Metro Rail Expo Line ar 4th st. and Colorado which you can take up to Exposition Park and the Science center if you want to see the beach and the Space Shuttle Endeavor all in one day. Trains come about every 20 minutes and its about 40 minute trip either way. Warning for some odd reason whoever designed the Metro Rail wasn't thinking about rest rooms so you may need to find one before you get on the train. No sweat, theres a mall just across the street  with public rest rooms on the second floor on the west side and one on the top floor on the north side in the food court past the bar and a Micky D's just a block further down towards the beach. Oh, there's a Cheesecake factory up on the top of the mall that has annadjacent patio with a great ocean view. If you take the train don't  forget to make it back in time for the sunset especially if you brought a date and you really like each other.< /text>
</record>
</dataset><record>
